he process has been key \u2013 to support the mandate for reform within national institutions and to encourage donors to align the cooperation they provide with country and regional priorities. Given their experience of the peer review process, Pacific Islands see SSC as an important delivery mechanism for the post-2015 agenda for building capacity, systems, and processes that can effectively deliver development results. figure 17 Pacific Islands undertaking peer reviews, 2010-2013 Source: Schuster (2014) Nauru, Kiribati Vanuatu Tuvalu Niue RMI Tonga PNG FSM Palau Solomon Islands Cook Islands Samoa 2010 2011 2012 2013 Source: PIFS, FIC Peer Review Reports 2010-2014 AsiA-PACifiC EffECtivE DEvEloPmEnt CooPERAtion REPoRt 82 Annex f. Government linked corporations in malaysia101 Government-linked corporations (GLCs)102 play a key role in the Malaysian economy and there are concerns that their dominance is crowding out investment in key sectors. GLCs account for at least 30% of net income in eight key sectors in Malaysia (Table 7) and are particularly dominant in utilities, transportation and warehousing, retail trade and banking. table 7. The share of GLCs in key sectors in Malaysia Total assets Net income Admin., Waste Management and Remediation Services 16.2% 35.8% Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting 42.9% 38.1% Banking 56.1% 58.3% Information and communications 67.1% 48.9% Retail trade 39.9% 60.2% Transportation and warehousing 78.8% 77.0% Transportation equipment manufacturing 28.0% 30.5% Utilities 88.4% 87.2% Source: Menon, J. and Hee Ng, T. (2013) Recent research103 by AsDB found that private investment is significantly lower in sectors in which GLCs are dominant, and private investments are greater in sectors in which GLCs do not play a significant role. This has been recognised by the government, which has called for a reduced role for government in business, and divestment programmes are in place in some sectors. Nevertheless, in some sectors GLCs continue to grow \u2013 notably in finance and property development. 101This case study is largely based on Are Government Linked Corporations Crowding Out Private Investment in Malaysia?, Menon, J., Hee Ng, T., 2013, Asian Development Bank 102Government linked corporations are defined as those in which the government owns a controlling stake in major decisions.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "dca0e7a6-adbc-42e4-8872-3a601ea81e60": {"__data__": {"id_": "dca0e7a6-adbc-42e4-8872-3a601ea81e60", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/asia-pacific-effective-development-co-operation-report-2014", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Asia-Pacific Effective Development Co-operation Report 2014", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/asia-pacific-effective-development-co-operation-report-2014", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b5b6a0c3714b836624b9a25d8c1c5b5dcf400c32300015b862835c040e9f4364"}, "2": {"node_id": "3ce9b3d2-a6cd-4c19-84ef-7fdcfcede04d", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/asia-pacific-effective-development-co-operation-report-2014", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0db8f60f3000a22798e564d0bb25c67a49c8399a16d42eb74afefcaffb4159d1"}}, "hash": "050afc97ca77a10f98f253d6c9def5b9cb4f75503b9538419d3937e9065ef287", "text": "103Are Government Linked Corporations Crowding Out Private Inv